<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#2f2f4f">Originally posted by Kydelian on 04-24-2001 06:13 PM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=10 COLS=45 WRAP="VIRTUAL">Wrong, wrong, wrong, Trawma.

Here are the facts - we all play the game to have fun.  We all have the "right" to enjoy the game in whatever fashion we choose so long as we that fashion doesn't impinge on anyone else's fun.

Once such a conflict occurs, which is greater, your right to have fun by "breaking down the walls with an army, killing everything in sight, and kill stealing Ragefire from the guy sitting there" or the guy who's sitting there's right to have fun by "sitting there camping it for days"?

Reality check: your right to have fun isn't any greater.  Nor does making your way sound more fun make it so.

Apparently you believe that the uber guilds are justified in doing whatever they want because "you are small, they are powerful".  You say "if you are trampled upon, it's because you are standing in the way of their fun".  Well, guess what, their fun isn't allowed to take precedence over that of anyone else's, small or not.

Suppose: Verant reinstitutes item loot, and a bunch of ubers decide to camp your bind spot and kill you til you're equipment-less.  After all, they are powerful, and you are small.  And for whatever lame reason they find it "fun".  Are you having fun?  This is a theoretical question, so don't bother telling me about all your uber friends.  They're all busy being camped by my imaginary uber legions anyway.  So?  Having fun?  

Sure, it's just a game.  But even in games there needs to be a standard of fairness.  Because of the very anonymity provided by the internet, some people decide to have fun by playing jerks (griefers, if you know the term).  Verant had to institute the Play Nice Policy just to keep these people in check.  Their world, their rules.  Might does not make right.  They left it up to the server communities to figure out how to share, but if the community can't agree, it comes down to random. 

Don't make the mistake of believing that the PNP doesn't have teeth.  People have been banned and guilds disbanded for PNP violations.

And don't hide behind "no one really gets hurt anyway".  No one invests the time that even a casual player puts into this game without developing some attachment to it.  There is a person behind the pixels, always.  That person has real feelings, whether you choose to recognize it or not.


[This message has been edited by Kydelian (edited 04-24-2001).]</TEXTAREA>
